    <h1>Strategy Guide</h1>

    <h2>Beginner Tips</h2>

    <h3>Canal Era Opening</h3>
    <div class="wiki-tip">
      The easiest opening is: build a cotton mill, connect it to any port, and sell it. This gets your income positive quickly and is the simplest path to understand.
    </div>
    <p>Other openings are perfectly viable. It's possible to open with heavy development and large loans.</p>

    <h3>Rail Era Preparation</h3>
    <div class="wiki-tip">
      Try to have some coal on the board at the beginning of the Rail Era. Build a Level 2+ coal mine near the end of the Canal Era. All rail tracks require coal, so there will be high demand.
    </div>

    <h2>Supply and Demand</h2>
    <p>Build whatever is in short supply:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Many unflipped cotton mills? Build ports to flip them.</li>
      <li>Many unflipped ports? Build cotton mills to use them.</li>
      <li>External coal market is low? Build coal mines - they'll empty and flip fast.</li>
      <li>External iron market is low? Build iron works.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Concentrating on what's in demand lets you flip industries faster, scoring income and VP sooner.</p>

    <h2>Income Management</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Loans are viable.</strong> At least one loan is generally necessary. Taking £30 is most efficient per action.</li>
      <li>Earlier loans are cheaper because lower income bands are smaller.</li>
      <li>Multiple loans over a game is a valid strategy.</li>
      <li>Getting income positive early (via cotton sales) is the safest beginner approach.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Link Strategy</h2>
    <div class="wiki-tip">
      Don't underestimate link VP! A link between two heavily-built locations can generate 5-7 VP on its own. In the Rail era, links are a major VP source.
    </div>
    <ul>
      <li>Build links where multiple industries will be flipped.</li>
      <li>Two rail links per action (£15 + 2 coal) is more efficient than building one at a time.</li>
      <li>Links also expand your personal network for future building.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Shipyards</h2>
    <p>Shipyards provide large VP (10 for L1, 18 for L2) and flip immediately when built. However:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>You must develop through Level 0 first (costs iron).</li>
      <li>Only available at Barrow-in-Furness and Birkenhead.</li>
      <li>Level 1 is Canal-only, Level 2 is Rail-only.</li>
      <li>Worth the investment if you can reach those locations efficiently.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Advanced Concepts</h2>

    <h3>Turn Order Manipulation</h3>
    <p>Spending less money in a round means going first next round. Going first is valuable because you get first pick of actions. Consider timing big purchases.</p>

    <h3>Overbuilding</h3>
    <p>In the Rail era, you can overbuild your own Level 1 tiles that survived the transition. You can also overbuild opponents' coal/iron if the external market is empty - use this aggressively.</p>

    <h3>Card Management</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Location cards are most flexible for building at specific spots.</li>
      <li>Industry cards are great when you want to build in your existing network.</li>
      <li>Any card works for loans, development, links, and passing.</li>
      <li>Plan your hand around your 2 actions per turn.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Scoring Awareness</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Canal era: flipped tiles + canal link VP. Level 1 tiles get removed, so don't over-invest in them.</li>
      <li>Rail era: flipped tiles + rail link VP + money/10. Everything counts here.</li>
      <li>Higher-level tiles give more VP but cost more to build. Balance investment vs. timing.</li>
    </ul>
